36:32.752 --> 36:43.905
That's why Jesus insisted that he could heal and restore and that his disciples could eat on the Sabbath because the Sabbath is meant to be something good that we experience and enjoy.

36:44.746 --> 36:52.135
We're supposed to do the things that replenish, restore, and rejuvenate our tired and weary souls.

36:52.275 --> 37:01.106
But if we're honest, many of us, if we've heard messages about this before or even heard the word, we incorrectly view Sabbath as boring.

37:01.986 --> 37:07.312
We picture it as a day or a period of time where we just sit around and do nothing.

37:07.412 --> 37:09.534
We stare at the ceiling, maybe doze off.

37:10.695 --> 37:15.120
Well, that might sound amazing to some and even to me, okay?

37:15.140 --> 37:17.342
Because I love a good nap and not doing anything.

37:17.422 --> 37:18.303
I'm fine with that.

37:18.944 --> 37:20.225
To others, I know you.

37:20.265 --> 37:23.809
To others, that sounds worse than a work day.

37:23.829 --> 37:29.074
A guy named John Tyson, Pastor in New York, he used a phrase I love when talking

37:29.282 --> 37:31.345
about the Sabbath and what we're supposed to do.

37:31.445 --> 37:33.187
He calls it pleasure stacking.

37:33.968 --> 37:42.219
In other words, on the Sabbath, we're supposed to do the things that bring us life and joy and then stack them together on top of one another.

37:42.279 --> 37:53.714
For example, I was reading a book about the Sabbath and this one author says that every Friday at 5 p.m., their Sabbath begins by baking this massive chocolate chip cookie.

37:54.594 --> 38:03.784
and then smothering it with vanilla ice cream while the cookies still warm, and then diving in with big spoons as a family before dinner.

38:05.946 --> 38:12.574
John Tyson, he talks about the really special coffee that he brews in his Chemex, if you like that sort of thing.

38:12.594 --> 38:18.640
The music he enjoys, the motorcycle rides that he takes, let me ask what brings you joy.

38:18.680 --> 38:20.402
Do those things.

38:20.962 --> 38:22.464
Do all of them in a period of time.

38:22.524 --> 38:23.605
Go for a long walk.

38:23.645 --> 38:24.346
Read a novel.

38:24.466 --> 38:25.287
Go to a movie.

38:25.728 --> 38:27.109
Play with your kids.

38:27.430 --> 38:28.792
Take a nap if you want.

38:28.872 --> 38:29.452
Work out.

38:29.512 --> 38:30.974
Visit your favorite coffee shop.

38:30.994 --> 38:31.675
Go fishing.

38:31.735 --> 38:32.856
Go ice fishing.

38:32.897 --> 38:33.517
That's miserable.

38:33.537 --> 38:34.238
Go golfing.

38:34.258 --> 38:39.485
Get down on the ground with your toddlers and play catch up with a friend historically.

38:39.545 --> 38:47.835
Jewish rabbis even encouraged married couples to enjoy sex as part of the Sabbath because the point is on the Sabbath.

38:48.235 --> 38:50.578
Do whatever brings you joy.

38:51.106 --> 38:57.532
Psalm 34, 8 says, taste and see that the Lord is good.

38:57.592 --> 39:03.598
He's Sabbath is meant to be this period of time that we taste and see the goodness of God and the things he's created.

39:04.619 --> 39:15.889
And I get that maybe that feels selfish, but like the good father that he is, like a good parent that he is, God wants us to fully embrace the gifts that he has provided us.

39:17.130 --> 39:17.931
Here's the key though.

39:18.872 --> 39:20.914
We got to do the things that bring us joy

39:21.186 --> 39:22.868
and replenish our souls.

39:23.529 --> 39:32.479
See, I'm all for watching a show or two on Netflix, but if I spent my entire Sabbath binge watching a full season, I would feel empty afterward.

39:33.260 --> 39:34.681
I know because I've done that.

39:34.741 --> 39:35.903
Okay, that's from practice.

39:37.324 --> 39:42.030
Do the things that fill your soul and fall within God's moral will that honor Him.

39:42.050 --> 39:46.795
Psalm 42 verse one through two says, as the deer pants for streams of water.

39:47.936 --> 39:49.458
So my soul pants for you.

39:50.402 --> 39:53.566
My soul thirsts for God for the living God.

39:53.706 --> 39:57.410
When can I go and meet with God?

39:57.671 --> 40:00.214
What are the things that quench your thirst for God?

40:00.975 --> 40:03.698
Brings you joy and then draws you closer to Him.

40:04.038 --> 40:05.720
Enjoy the gift of Sabbath.

40:05.800 --> 40:07.823
Do whatever brings you joy.

40:08.644 --> 40:12.909
Second way to embrace Sabbath and do a well is to stop doing more.

40:13.950 --> 40:17.074
Everything in culture pushes us to do more.

40:17.730 --> 40:24.519
Work more, achieve more, buy more, sign up for more, consume more, schedule more, post more, prove more.

40:24.539 --> 40:27.924
We're constantly hearing messages like, go big or go home.

40:28.946 --> 40:31.369
You gotta crush the hustle, never slow down.

40:31.409 --> 40:32.711
You get one life to live.

40:33.692 --> 40:38.219
And listen, I'm all for working hard, planning well, and pursuing big dreams.

40:38.259 --> 40:41.743
But after 42 years, I've realized something.

40:42.665 --> 40:46.450
Those messages don't usually deliver on what they promise.

40:47.138 --> 40:53.487
See, most people that I know who live at that kind of frenetic pace eventually burn out, break down, or blow up.

40:54.369 --> 40:55.631
So what does the Sabbath do?

40:56.512 --> 41:01.640
Sabbath gives us the chance to resist this cultural narrative that more is always better.

41:02.481 --> 41:08.270
Just for a period of time to stop striving, stop proving, and stop performing.

41:08.971 --> 41:11.454
Psalm 46, 10, Jason shared this last week.

41:12.596 --> 41:13.938
That says, be still.

41:15.266 --> 41:17.088
be still and know that I am God.

41:18.150 --> 41:27.161
Sabbath is this day we get to be still long enough to intentionally reflect on questions like, who is truly in control of my life?

41:28.743 --> 41:30.425
Who ultimately provides for me?

41:30.485 --> 41:32.448
Who sustains my life?

41:32.628 --> 41:34.130
Is it me or is it God?

41:35.051 --> 41:42.620
Because it's the day we stop long enough to let our minds and bodies catch up from everything else we cease from doing more.

41:42.640 --> 41:43.922
Now, practically,

41:44.034 --> 41:45.236
what might we cease from?

41:45.316 --> 41:50.545
And I know we're all in different periods of our lives, but here's just a few ideas.

41:50.625 --> 41:54.912
Maybe it's just email, social media, the phone, just set it aside.

41:54.992 --> 42:01.963
Just anything that feels like I'm trying to achieve schoolwork, students, you can use this one for just a short little window of time.

42:02.304 --> 42:11.218
To do list, household chores, shopping, unless going to Costco genuinely feels your soul like it does mine, then you can go ahead, okay?

42:11.874 --> 42:13.677
But the point is, these aren't rules.

42:13.717 --> 42:15.740
That's why Jesus tried to break this all down.

42:16.020 --> 42:18.764
You can figure out what feels like more or not.

42:18.824 --> 42:29.400
The point is choose to lay down everything that feels like work or burdensome for one period of time a week.

42:29.500 --> 42:34.207
And it's an act of faith because it reminds us, God is God.

42:34.728 --> 42:35.288
I am not.

42:35.349 --> 42:36.971
And so we stop.

42:37.872 --> 42:41.778
We trust and we stop doing

42:41.922 --> 42:42.182
more.

42:43.044 --> 42:46.290
The third way to embrace Sabbath well is to put it on the calendar.

42:46.310 --> 42:52.040
A couple of years ago, I set out to complete a triathlon.

42:52.060 --> 42:56.668
It was just, I've told this before, but it was on a list of things I wanted to do before I turned 40, swim, bike run.

42:56.708 --> 42:59.232
I mean, I thought, how hard this could, you know, could this be?

42:59.813 --> 43:03.299
And because I run, you know, I can pedal a bike and swimming.

43:03.740 --> 43:05.042
I've been there, done that.

43:05.538 --> 43:16.593
But never mind that prior to this, an orthopedic surgeon had taken a look at the scans of both of my knees earlier that year and said, you know, you should probably hang up the running shoes.

43:17.294 --> 43:26.226
Never mind, I didn't own a real bike that my helmet was way too small for my large head and I had never worn a wetsuit

43:26.338 --> 43:28.861
or swam in open waters before.

43:28.961 --> 43:34.769
I was just determined, so I got to training, you know, 12-week plan, swimming, biking, running, big deal.

43:34.849 --> 43:35.329
I was ready.

43:35.710 --> 43:48.786
But on race day, when I stood on the shores of White Bear Lake and looked out at the buoy's stretch across White Bear, marking how far we had to swim, I thought, oh, no.

43:50.530 --> 43:51.371
What have I done?

43:51.451 --> 44:02.444
Because up until that point, my swimming had consisted of these 25-yard laps in a pool where I could rest my arms on the wall every time I got tired.

44:03.285 --> 44:04.246
This was not that.

44:05.067 --> 44:07.630
So once the race began, reality set in.

44:07.690 --> 44:17.682
I went from this confident freestyle to a breaststroke to a side stroke to simply lying on my back and letting the wetsuit float me like a pool noodle.

44:19.042 --> 44:21.665
Every time I looked up, I thought, why am I doing this?

44:21.765 --> 44:23.867
I should just let the rescue boat haul me in.

44:25.009 --> 44:30.375
Well, what I didn't know at the time was that about halfway out in the lake, the water was low enough to stand.

44:30.395 --> 44:32.137
There was a sandbar right in the middle.

44:32.777 --> 44:35.560
So halfway through the swim, I walked.

44:36.641 --> 44:37.583
I took a breather.

44:37.603 --> 44:46.372
I regained my strength and I managed to finish the swim second to last, which means that I beat someone.

44:46.552 --> 44:47.954
Okay, let's not forget that.

44:50.114 --> 44:52.178
But you know, looking back, I realized something.

44:52.218 --> 44:56.425
If I had known that this break was coming, that I could walk at the turnaround point.

44:57.186 --> 45:02.115
If I had known there was a place to rest about halfway through, I think I would have swam differently.

45:02.135 --> 45:09.668
I at least would have had more peace that I was going to make it, maybe had more energy, more confidence, more joy, maybe even taken third to last.

45:09.728 --> 45:10.289
You never know.

45:10.349 --> 45:12.293
I mean, I could have passed out of the person.

45:12.333 --> 45:15.218
That's what the Sabbath is meant to be.

45:16.034 --> 45:22.061
It's meant to be this built-in break, a weekly pause, part of the flow and rhythm of our lives.

45:22.102 --> 45:27.949
One day, one stretch of time, a weekly sandbar, and it's not gonna happen on accident.

45:28.770 --> 45:30.051
So you gotta put it on the calendar.

45:30.832 --> 45:36.139
Now just, let me back up a second and remind you Jesus doesn't want us to get legalistic about this.

45:37.020 --> 45:45.170
It doesn't have to be the same 24-hour window for everyone, and maybe for some of us 24 hours feels impossible.

45:45.634 --> 45:49.578
So start with six hours, or maybe 12.

45:50.258 --> 45:55.123
Personally, for me, I aim for Friday at noon to Saturday at noon.

45:55.243 --> 45:56.584
It fits the flow of my week.

45:56.624 --> 45:58.526
Yes, I still have to take care of my kids.

45:58.566 --> 46:02.750
There's things I gotta do, but put it on the calendar where it fits.

46:03.271 --> 46:05.673
For you, even athletes know you can't train 24-7.

46:07.315 --> 46:10.197
Muscles need time to replenish, restore, and repair.

46:10.638 --> 46:14.962
If they don't, they break down and our souls are no different.

46:15.490 --> 46:24.580
So without this planned rhythm of rest, we do eventually break, but with each planned Sabbath, our souls have time to refuel.

46:25.521 --> 46:36.513
Jesus said this in John chapter 10, verse 10, he says, I have come that they may have life and have life to the full.

46:36.634 --> 46:44.242
He's Sabbath creates the space in our lives to receive the fullness of life that Jesus promises.

46:44.738 --> 46:53.047
Like Jason taught a couple of weeks ago to refill what work and life drains to restore what gets depleted.

46:53.708 --> 46:56.371
So make Sabbath a part of the rhythm of your week.

46:56.391 --> 46:57.312
Put it on the calendar.

46:58.033 --> 47:01.997
Fourth way, to embrace Sabbath as well as to be with Jesus.

47:03.339 --> 47:06.863
There's this profound scene in John chapter 13.

47:06.883 --> 47:12.008
Now it's become what's known as the Last Supper, Jesus, the sitting around, the disciples.

47:12.068 --> 47:13.490
He knows his time on earth.

47:14.178 --> 47:21.669
is almost over and he wants to show his disciples what love truly looks like.

47:21.689 --> 47:30.222
And so he gets up from the table, he wraps a towel around his waist and he begins washing the disciples' feet, something only at the time a servant would have done.

47:31.264 --> 47:36.412
But Jesus is flipping the idea of power and sacrificial love completely upside down.

47:36.492 --> 47:43.122
And then in the middle of this scene, John the author includes a detail that I've missed before, I don't miss it anymore.

47:43.522 --> 47:44.724
And I don't want you to miss.

47:45.645 --> 47:54.059
In John 13, verse 23, it says one of them, the disciple whom Jesus loved was reclining next to him.

47:55.100 --> 48:00.529
Now this is John, the disciple, writing this about himself.

48:00.589 --> 48:01.431
And I love this.

48:02.532 --> 48:03.914
I love that confidence.

48:04.756 --> 48:07.120
John is saying, I'm the one Jesus loves.

48:07.981 --> 48:08.602
And guess what?

48:08.702 --> 48:11.186
You and I can say the exact same thing.

48:11.938 --> 48:13.801
I'm the one that Jesus loves.

48:14.742 --> 48:16.184
He wants to hang out with us.

48:16.845 --> 48:17.766
He likes us.

48:18.928 --> 48:24.876
And then in verse 25, it says, leaning back against Jesus.

48:25.757 --> 48:27.840
I just want you to picture this scene for a moment.

48:28.861 --> 48:34.549
In a world that typically gets uncomfortable with physical closeness, John is so comfortable with Jesus.

48:35.230 --> 48:41.138
So secure in their relationship and their friendship and their love that he literally leans back against him.

48:42.018 --> 48:46.463
See, that's the deepest, most loving and intimate kind of relationship there is.

48:47.365 --> 48:53.452
And Sabbath is meant to remind us that we also can have that kind of relationship with Jesus.

48:54.293 --> 48:56.095
He is the one we can lean back on.

48:57.117 --> 48:58.418
He is our ultimate rest.

48:58.518 --> 49:03.044
He is the one who restores and satisfies our weary souls.

49:03.084 --> 49:07.029
The ultimate gift of Sabbath is Jesus himself.

49:07.069 --> 49:08.691
So we have to learn to be with him.

49:09.532 --> 49:11.154
I love how Eugene Peterson

49:11.650 --> 49:15.916
paraphrases Matthew 11 verse 28 through 30 in the message.

49:16.757 --> 49:24.849
And this is Jesus speaking, says, are you tired, worn out, burned out on religion?

49:25.890 --> 49:26.471
Come to me.

49:27.453 --> 49:29.495
Get away with me and you'll recover your life.

49:29.756 --> 49:32.580
I'll show you how to take a real rest.

49:33.541 --> 49:34.943
Walk with me and work with me.

49:35.925 --> 49:36.946
Watch how I do it.

49:37.890 --> 49:40.113
Learn the unforced rhythms of grace.

49:40.173 --> 49:43.016
I won't lay anything heavy or ill-fitting on you.

49:43.036 --> 49:51.387
Jesus says, keep company with me, and you'll learn to live freely and lightly on the Sabbath.

49:51.467 --> 49:53.770
Keep company with Jesus.

49:53.990 --> 49:55.852
Now, practically, what does that look like?

49:55.892 --> 50:00.338
It means prayer, talking to Jesus, tell them how you're feeling.

50:00.802 --> 50:03.245
Spend some additional time reading the word.

50:03.285 --> 50:04.547
Read a Christian book.

50:04.867 --> 50:06.229
Listen to worship music.

50:06.249 --> 50:08.231
Do whatever draws you closer to Jesus.

50:08.291 --> 50:09.012
Go outside.

50:09.072 --> 50:10.073
Be with Him.

50:10.674 --> 50:18.764
Just envision Him around your life as you go about your day because rest is ultimately found in a relationship with Jesus.

50:18.824 --> 50:20.987
We have to learn to be with Him.

50:22.108 --> 50:23.730
Final way is this, it's worship.

50:24.674 --> 50:31.462
Now, when we hear the word worship, we often think of singing, and worship absolutely includes singing, but it's far more than that.

50:31.942 --> 50:40.132
Worship, ultimately, is directing our attention, our affection, and our lives back toward God.

50:41.253 --> 50:49.843
And Sabbath gives us this weekly space to remember what matters most and who is deserving of our attention and affection.

50:49.863 --> 50:52.306
See, on the Sabbath, we turn our hearts

50:53.026 --> 50:56.654
toward the only one who is worthy of our lives, we worship Jesus.

50:57.756 --> 51:05.713
And as we head into Christmas next week, it's worth remembering when Jesus was born, nothing was calm in the world at all.

51:06.875 --> 51:11.986
There was this teenage couple explaining a miracle that no one really believed.

51:12.258 --> 51:18.787
They had a forced journey to Bethlehem, a birth and a manger, then a violent king who was ordering other infants to be killed.

51:19.188 --> 51:21.171
No peace, no stability.

51:21.311 --> 51:28.381
And yet, as Louis Giglio said, in this manger, somehow there is a promise of peace.

51:28.441 --> 51:40.658
See, on the Sabbath, we pause and we remember and we will worship the Savior who was born in a manger and came into this chaos to bring

51:41.250 --> 51:45.916
promise of peace, which is what happened on Christmas Eve in 1914.

51:46.056 --> 51:53.085
It's right there in the middle of World War I, which had become the deadliest conflict in history.

51:53.145 --> 51:59.353
British and German soldiers sat exhausted in freezing trenches across from one another.

52:00.434 --> 52:09.586
But then, a melody drifted across the battlefield, first from the Germans, still knocked, followed closely by the British and English silent night.

52:10.306 --> 52:18.659
And moments later, both sides were singing Silent Night, Holy Night, all is calm, all is bright.

52:19.700 --> 52:32.220
Right there in the middle of no man's land, which was considered the most dangerous place on earth at the time, they exchanged gifts, buried the dead, and prayed for one night there was peace because they worshiped.

52:33.642 --> 52:36.306
See, maybe you've been trying to do life your way.

52:36.930 --> 52:39.773
without this practice, this break of Sabbath.

52:39.833 --> 52:43.677
But what if this was your Fosbury flop type of moment?

52:44.618 --> 52:50.064
What if this was the time to incorporate a new way and approach to doing life?

52:51.125 --> 52:54.528
So as we conclude, here's my very practical challenge.

52:55.309 --> 52:56.290
Can you guess what it is?

52:56.310 --> 52:58.472
It's to choose a Sabbath.

52:59.413 --> 53:04.018
This week, Christmas is a perfect time to give it a go.

53:04.610 --> 53:06.713
Ultimately, Christmas is Sabbath.

53:06.773 --> 53:07.774
You enjoy gifts.

53:07.794 --> 53:08.836
You be with one another.

53:08.896 --> 53:12.040
You turn your attention to the Savior of the world.

53:12.100 --> 53:16.506
So experiment, make space, and then plan for it in 2026.

53:18.088 --> 53:20.291
Reminder, do whatever brings you joy.

53:20.392 --> 53:21.393
Stop doing more.

53:21.513 --> 53:22.595
Put it on the calendar.

53:23.095 --> 53:28.322
Be with Jesus and worship for whatever period of time that you can carve out.

53:29.784 --> 53:33.970
But as we close this series, we wanted to create one more moment of worship for you.

53:35.298 --> 53:38.003
to provide some space for you.

53:38.063 --> 53:54.130
And we rarely get this kind of space, but for the next five minutes to just sit under a song and allow God to restore and replenish your soul as you fix your attention on Him.

53:55.633 --> 54:01.202
So as we sit under this and take in this beautiful next song, just allow God

54:02.466 --> 54:13.778
to re-center your mind and your soul and your heart as we are reminded about this thrill of hope, the night that Christ

59:51.490 --> 59:54.914
I forgot for you to experience God's peace, Heavenly Father.

59:54.974 --> 59:57.177
Thank you for who you are.

59:58.498 --> 01:00:00.320
Thank you for sending your son, Jesus.

01:00:01.782 --> 01:00:04.906
And I know that so many people are experiencing so much.

01:00:06.608 --> 01:00:07.629
All is not calm.

01:00:08.730 --> 01:00:16.479
And yet, somehow, in the birth of your son, Jesus, in that manger, there is a promise of peace.

01:00:16.619 --> 01:00:19.122
And so by faith, we cling to that.

01:00:20.546 --> 01:00:32.284
We turn our attention, our affection towards you this season, no matter the busyness or the grief or the emotions that we're feeling or maybe just the normalcy of life.

01:00:34.106 --> 01:00:47.186
God, we pray for just a reminder to be directed back to you, to turn our attention to you and that we had experienced the good things that you have given us despite some of the troubles.

01:00:47.842 --> 01:00:55.732
Now we pray for Christmas, we pray that all that you are going to do Lord, we pray that people would turn to you maybe for the first time and we pray gone.

01:00:56.053 --> 01:00:58.636
The ultimately we'd find our rest and our hope in you.

01:00:59.377 --> 01:01:01.960
Thank you for this opportunity to worship you today.

01:01:02.441 --> 01:01:05.265
We pray this all in Jesus name, amen.

01:01:06.086 --> 01:01:09.670
If you'd like prayer, we'll have a prayer team down front who would love to pray with you.

01:01:10.071 --> 01:01:12.434
Otherwise we'll see you next week for our Christmas services.

